Broadway (police thereon), north from Queens Boulevard, showing at the left on the N.W. corner the Heeg Hotel erected by John Heeg in 1891. This structure was partially demolished in October 1930. Portions of it, however, still remain.

March 1923.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

Queens Boulevard, north side, west of Broadway to Van Loon Street. Eugene L. Armbruster states that the building in the foreground was the original Baptist Church of Elmhurst and that it was erected in 1809. This structure originally stood on the Jamaica Road, south side, east of Horse Brook Road, and was moved to Grand Street in 1857 and remodeled (opposite Town Hall?) and from the last location was moved to the present site.

January 1923.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

Queens Boulevard (foreground), north side, at Broadway (center), showing at the N.W. corner of same, the Heeg Hotel, erected by John Heeg in 1891. This structure, partially demolished in October 1930, still remains in part today (1938). Through the center appears a northward view on Broadway, which curves westward from this point, and upon which runs the newly constructed Independent Subway. (1934)

March 1923.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection
